                    <comment id="12379317" author="jsdever@sympatico.ca" created="Mon, 8 Jul 2002 22:51:36 +0100"  >Should also add a method:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
void addParameter(NameValuePair parameter)&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
                    <comment id="12379318" author="jsdever@sympatico.ca" created="Mon, 8 Jul 2002 22:56:46 +0100"  >The addParameter methods that are in the PostMethod should actually be moved &lt;br/&gt;
out to the base class GetMethod and mabye even higher into HttpMethodBase.  It &lt;br/&gt;
does make sense for a GET to have parameters: they are in the query string as &lt;br/&gt;
opposed to a POST which are url encoded and send in the body.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
The ease in which a form can be submitted in a html page using either GET or &lt;br/&gt;
POST should be parallel to the GetMethod and PostMethod.&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;</comment>
                    <comment id="12379319" author="jsdever@sympatico.ca" created="Tue, 9 Jul 2002 10:44:52 +0100"  >&lt;br/&gt;
Only POST methods (afaik) take a x-www-form-urlencoded content header,&lt;br/&gt;
which seems to be the purpose of the setParameter and such methods.   The&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;quot;parameters&amp;quot; would be urlencoded (using URIUtil.encode presumably) and&lt;br/&gt;
stuffed in the content body.   The query string, if any, remains part of&lt;br/&gt;
the URL.  The query string and the parameters are independant so it does&lt;br/&gt;
makes sense that there are different methods to handle them, as it is&lt;br/&gt;
currently.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
It would just be nice to add a bunch of parameters as a NameValuePair&lt;br/&gt;
array in the same way that you already can with the query string.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
